## **0\. What We‚Äôre Building (Context)**

You will build **Lumina** ‚Äî a Photo-to-Video AI web app that:

* takes a product URL or images,  
* generates short AI videos using **Google Veo**,  
* authenticates users via **Google OAuth (Supabase)**,  
* optionally saves videos to **Google Drive**, and  
* runs as a real deployed web app.

This is a **build session**, not a demo.

## **1\. Setting Up Your Tools (Node.js & npm)** {#1.-setting-up-your-tools-(node.js-&-npm)}

First, we need to install the engine that will run our application. Think of **Node.js** as the engine and **npm** (Node Package Manager) as the toolbelt that helps you install add-ons.

### **For Mac Users**

#### ![][image1]

1. Go to the [Node.js Website](https://nodejs.org/en/download).  
2. Download the **LTS (Long Term Support)** version. This is the most stable version.  
3. Open the downloaded file and follow the installer instructions (mostly just clicking "Continue").  
4. To verify, open your **Terminal** app (Command \+ Space, type "Terminal") and type the following commands:  
   * `node -v`  
   * `npm -v`  
5. If you see numbers popping up, you're good to go\!

   ### **For Windows Users**

   #### ![][image2]

1. Go to the [Node.js Website](https://nodejs.org/en/download).  
2. Download the **LTS (Long Term Support)** version.  
3. Run the installer. **Important:** Make sure the checkbox saying **"Add to PATH"** is checked during installation.  
4. To verify, open **Command Prompt** (Start, type "cmd") or PowerShell and type the following commands:  
   * `node -v`  
   * `npm -v`  
5. If you see numbers popping up, you're good to go\!

## **5\. Supabase Setup (Auth \+ Database)** {#5.-supabase-setup-(auth-+-database)}

We will use **Supabase** to store webapp user actions or system events.

* It is a hosted database service (it manages the "Excel sheets" for us).  
* It's incredibly easy to talk to from our app.  
* It handles things like **User Login** (Authentication) automatically, so we don't have to build complex security systems from scratch.

  ### **Setup Instructions for Supabase**

* **Create an Account:**  
  * Go to [supabase.com](https://supabase.com/).  
  * Click "Start your project" and signup/login using email-id/password.  
  * \[If Sign-Up\] Check your email to confirm the account  
    ![][image38]  
  * \[If Sign-Up\] Create a new organization with any name & type you like. Keep the plan to ‚ÄúFree \- $0/month‚Äù.  
    ![][image39]  
* **Create a Project:**  
  * \[If existing user\] Click "New Project" & Choose an organization.  
  * **Name:** Give it a cool name (e.g., "lumina").  
  * **Database Password:** Generate a strong password and **COPY IT** to a safe place (you won't see it again\!).  
  * **Region:** Choose a location close to you. "Asia-Pacific‚Äù is good to go.  
  * Click "Create new project".  
    ![][image40]  
* **Get Your API Keys (The Secret Passwords):**  
  * Once the project is created, go to the **Project** **Settings** icon (cogwheel) at the bottom left.  
  * Click on **Data API** under Project Settings.  
    * **Project URL:** Copy this & paste it in a digital note.  
      ![][image41]  
  * Click on **API Keys** under Project Settings  
    * **Project API Keys (anon public):** Copy this & paste it in a digital note.  
    * *Note: Never share the "service\_role" key with anyone as it can be used to hack into your supabase databases.*  
      *![][image42]*  
* **Enable Auth on Supabase**  
  * Supabase ‚Üí Project Settings \-\> Authentication ‚Üí Sign In / Providers ‚Üí Find ‚ÄúGoogle‚Äù under Auth Providers.  
  * Click on ‚ÄúGoogle‚Äù & a side-bar would popup  
  * Click on toggle at the top of the side-bar to ‚ÄúEnable Sign in with Google‚Äù  
  * Copy Callback URL (for OAuth) from the bottom of the sidebar. Format: https://*\<your-supabase-ref\>*.supabase.co/auth/v1/callback  
    ![][image43]  
  * [Add Client ID & Secret (Get from Google Cloud)](#3.-google-cloud-console-setup-\(auth-+-gemini/veo\))  
  * Go back to [https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials](https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials)   
    * Click on OAuth 2.0 Client IDs link (like how ‚Äúlumina‚Äù link is below)  
      ![][image44]  
    * Add Callback URL to Authorized redirect URIs & Save.  
    * ![][image45]  
  * Click ‚ÄúSave‚Äù on supabase sidebar too & you should see Enabled Google now.  
    ![][image46]  
  * Finally, go to ‚ÄúURL Configuration‚Äù under Authentication  
    * Site URL: Add [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) if not already added  
    * Redirect URLs: Add [http://localhost:3000/\*](http://localhost:3000/*) if not already added  
      **![][image47]**  
* **Database Tables**  
  * We will create minimal tables for:  
    * Usage tracking ‚Äúuser\_usage‚Äù:   
    * Video logs ‚Äúvideo\_logs‚Äù:   
    * Image scraping logs ‚Äúscrape\_logs‚Äù:   
  * Go to ‚ÄúSQL Editor‚Äù to add above tables  
    ![][image48]  
  * As per the below image, you should see three tables in ‚ÄúTable Editor‚Äù after successfully running the sql queries  
    ![][image49]

# **\[Learning Corner\]**

## **1\. What is the Frontend?**

Imagine a fancy restaurant.

* **The Frontend** is the dining room where the customers (users) sit.  
* It's everything you can **see, touch, and interact with**: the nicely decorated tables, the menu, the lighting, and the waiters.  
* In technical terms, this is what runs in your web browser (Chrome, Safari). It's buttons, images, text, and animations.  
* **Goal:** To make things look beautiful and feel smooth (the "vibe").

  ### **UI vs. UX (The Decor vs. The Comfort)**

* **UI (User Interface):** This is the decoration. The color of the paint, the font on the menu, the plating of the food. It's strictly about **how it looks**.  
* **UX (User Experience):** This is the feeling. Is the chair comfortable? Is the menu easy to read? Does the waiter come when you call? It's about **how it works and feels**. A beautiful chair that hurts to sit on has good UI but bad UX.

  ## **2\. What is the Backend?**

Now, think about what happens behind the swing doors of that restaurant.

* **The Backend** is the kitchen. The customers never see it, but the restaurant can't function without it.  
* It handles the **logic and processing**.  
* When you order food (click a "Buy" button), the waiter tells the kitchen (Backend). The kitchen checks if they have ingredients, cooks the meal, and hands it back to the waiter.  
* It handles things like processing payments, sending emails, or verifying your password.

  ### **Backend Architecture (The Kitchen Stations)**

A professional kitchen isn't just one messy pile of food. It's organized.

* **Architecture** is simply how we organize the code.  
* You have the "Grill Station" (Handling Users), the "Salad Station" (Handling Payments), and the "Dessert Station" (Sending Emails).  
* Good architecture means the salad chef doesn't get in the way of the grill chef.

  ### **What is an API?**

* You (the Customer/Frontend) never go into the kitchen (Backend) to cook your own burger. That would be chaotic.  
* Instead, you talk to the **Waiter**.  
* **API (Application Programming Interface)** is the waiter.  
* You give the waiter an order ("I want 1 burger"). This is a **Request**.  
* The waiter takes it to the kitchen, gets the burger, and brings it back to you. This is a **Response**.

  ## **3\. What is a Database?**

Imagine the restaurant manager uses a massive Excel file to track everything.

* **A Database** is essentially a collection of super-powered Excel sheets that live in the cloud.  
* **Tables:** Just like tabs in Excel. You might have a "Users" tab and a "Orders" tab.  
* **Rows & Columns:** A row is one specific user (e.g., "John Doe"), and columns are their details (e.g., "Email," "Phone Number").  
* **Relations:** This is the magic part. We can link rows. For example, an order in the "Orders" sheet can point to "John Doe" in the "Users" sheet, so we know who bought what.

  ### **What is "The Cloud"?**

* When you cook at home, you're using your own stove. If your stove breaks, you can't cook.  
* **The Cloud** is like renting a massive, indestructible professional kitchen that someone else manages.  
* Instead of saving data on your laptop (which could get lost or run out of space), we save it on "The Cloud" (massive computers owned by companies like Google, Amazon, or Supabase) so it's safe and accessible from anywhere in the world.
